urt’s early life was indeed a triumph of wit and will. He managed to escape a world filled with violence and a culture that valued street smarts over book smarts, all the while knowing that just about everyone around him thought little of his prospects. That he made it out at all is extraordinary. That he became a successful lawyer and writer is virtually unimaginable.” —Commonweal “Dan Burt is a fine poet, and this memoir has all the sensitivity and vigilance you might expect from a writer with such a background. But his prose also has a robustness and documentary power that continually startles and engages. As it combines these things, You Think It Strange catches the strangeness of the world and makes it familiar.” —Sir Andrew Motion, Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom, 1999-2009  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAmericanszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aPoets, Englishy21st centuryvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aémigré, St John’s College, the American Dream, Dan Burt, memoir, memoirs, American émigré, immigrant stories, immigration, Jewish immigrants, educational journey, spiritual journey, working-class stories, self discovery, CBS vs. Westmoreland, La Salle, exceptionalism, ex-pat, Cambridge University.40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978830165?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978830165423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978830165/original  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK